9–1099","1080–Male":"1080–Afdød","1216–1272":"1216–1272","1000–Male":"1000–Afdød","1020–Female":"1020–Afdød","1080":"1080","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1099":"1099","1086":"1086","1020":"1020","1096":"1096","1272":"1272","1195":"1195","1060":"1060","1216":"1216","1106":"1106","1059":"1059","1213":"1213","1045":"1045","about 1059":"omkring 1059","Normandy, France or Hereford England":"Normandie, Frankrig","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","Breteuil, Normandy, France":"Breteuil-sur-Iton, Eure, Normandie, Frankrig"},"nl":{"1045–":"1045–Overleden","1045–Male":"1045–Overleden","1195–1213":"1195–1213","1060–Female":"1060–Overleden","1059–1099":"1059–1099","1080–Male":"1080–Overleden","1216–1272":"1216–1272","1000–Male":"1000–Overleden","1020–Female":"1020–Overleden","1080":"1080","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1099":"1099","1086":"1086","1020":"1020","1096":"1096","1272":"1272","1195":"1195","1060":"1060","1216":"1216","1106":"1106","1059":"1059","1213":"1213","1045":"1045","about 1059":"circa 1059","Normandy, France or Hereford England":"Normandie, Frankrijk","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","Breteuil, Normandy, France":"Breteuil-sur-Iton, Eure, Normandie, Frankrijk"},"en":{"1045–":"1045–Deceased","1045–Male":"1045–Deceased","1195–1213":"1195–1213","1060–Female":"1060–Deceased","1059–1099":"1059–1099","1080–Male":"1080–Deceased","1216–1272":"1216–1272","1000–Male":"1000–Deceased","1020–Female":"1020–Deceased","1080":"1080","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1099":"1099","1086":"1086","1020":"1020","1096":"1096","1272":"1272","1195":"1195","1060":"1060","1216":"1216","1106":"1106","1059":"1059","1213":"1213","1045":"1045","about 1059":"about 1059","Normandy, France or Hereford England":"Normandy, France","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","Breteuil, Normandy, France":"Breteuil-sur-Iton, Eure, Normandy, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Osborne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Osbern</i>, partly from late Old English <i>Ōsbern</i>, an Anglicized form of Old Norse <i>Ásbiǫrn</i> (from <i>áss</i> ‘god’ + <i>biǫrn</i> ‘bear’), but more usually from Norman use of the cognate ancient Germanic <i>Ōsbern</i>. <i>Osbern</i> was often treated as an alternative form of <i>Osbert</i>. For pet forms see   Hoskin   and   Opie  . The surname has also been established in Ireland (Waterford, Tipperary) since the mid 16th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Osbon","meanings":["English (Sussex): variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Osbourn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Osbourne","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Oborne","meanings":["English:","habitational name from Oborne in Dorset. The placename derives from Old English <i>wōh</i> ‘twisted, crooked’ + <i>burna</i> ‘spring, stream’.","possibly from the Middle English personal name <i>Obern</i>, an Anglo-Norman French form of <i>Osbern</i> (see   Osborne  )."]},{"name":"Orsburn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Osbun","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Hoskin","meanings":["English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Osekin</i> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, a pet form of Anglo-Norman French names beginning with <i>Os-</i> (particularly <i>Osbert</i>, as well as <i>Osbern</i>, and <i>Osmund</i>) + the Flemish diminutive suffix <i>-kin</i>. All three personal names were current in medieval Cornwall or Devon; see   Osborne  ,   Osmond  , and   Opie   (a pet form of <i>Osbert</i>). Old English <i>Ōsbeorn</i>, <i>Ōsbeohrt</i>, and <i>Ōsmund</i> may also have contributed in a minor way to Middle English usage; Middle English   Oswald   is another possible source, but the name was very rare in the late 14th century. For the excrescent initial <i>H-</i>, compare   Herrick  ."]},{"name":"Osborn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Orsborn","meanings":["English: variant of   Osborne  ."]},{"name":"Oborn","meanings":["English (Somerset): habitational name chiefly from Oborne in Dorset, or perhaps occasionally from Howbourne Farm in Hadlow Down, Sussex, Woburn in Bedfordshire, Woburn Park in Surrey, or Wooburn in Buckinghamshire. The placenames derive from Old English <i>wōh</i> ‘twisted, crooked’ + <i>burna</i> ‘spring, stream’, except Wooburn in Buckinghamshire, which is of uncertain etymology.","English (of Norman origin): perhaps from the Middle English personal name <i>Obern</i>, an Anglo-Norman French form of <i>Osbern</i> (see   Osborne  )."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]},{"name":"Fitz","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Either a short form of any of the numerous names representing a transferred use of a surname formed with the Anglo-Norman French prefix <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son of ’, as for example   Fitzgerald  ,   Fitzroy  , or a transferred use of the surname <i>Fitz</i>, which may be of the same derivation, but applied originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same given name, or a local name from Fitz in Shropshire, named with the Old English personal name <i>Fitt</i> + <i>hōh</i> ‘hill spur’."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":21,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705183,"age":41,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705184,"age":51,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705185,"age":61,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Richard Fitz Osborne was born in 1045, in Herefordshire, England, his father, Count of Brionne Gilbert Osborne, was 45 and his mother, Rohese Gifford, was 25. He had at least 2 sons and 1 daughter with Nesta verch Gwynedd."},"et":{"1045–":"1045–Surnud","1045–Male":"1045–Surnud","1195–1213":"1195–1213","1060–Female":"1060–Surnud","1059–1099":"1059–1099","1080–Male":"1080–Surnud","1216–1272":"1216–1272","1000–Male":"1000–Surnud","1020–Female":"1020–Surnud","1080":"1080","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1099":"1099","1086":"1086","1020":"1020","1096":"1096","1272":"1272","1195":"1195","1060":"1060","1216":"1216","1106":"1106","1059":"1059","1213":"1213","1045":"1045","about 1059":"umbes 1059","Normandy, France or Hereford England":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Herefordshire, England":"Herefordshire, England","Breteuil, Normandy, France":"Breteuil-sur-Iton, Eure, Normandie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1045–":"1045–Kuollut","1045–Male":"1045–Kuollut","1195–1213":"1195–1213","1060–Female":"1060–Kuollut","1059–1099":"1059–1099","1080–Male":"1080–Kuollut","1216–1272":"1216–1272","1000–Male":"1000–Kuollut","1020–Female":"1020–Kuollut","1080":"1080","1066":"1066","1000":"1000","1099":"1099","1086":"1086","1020":"1020","1096":"1096","1272":"1272","1195":"1195","1060":"1060","1216":"1216","1106":"1106","1059":"1059","1213":"1213","1045":"1045","about 1059":"noin 1059","Normandy, France or Hereford England":"Normandie, Ranska","Herefordshire,